Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the noodles.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{125%grams} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Quarter the @lime{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch} (stalks and all).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Drain the @king prawns{150%grams}.  
> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Once hot, add the sliced pepper, @sliced mushrooms{180%grams} and prawns. Fry until the prawns are cooked through and the veg has softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Continue to stir while it cooks. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Once hot, add the prawns. Season with salt and pepper and stir-fry for ~{4-5%minutes}. Once cooked, remove the frying pan from the heat.  
> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add the garlic and @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} to the pan. Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @soy sauce{25%ml}, @ketjap manis{50%grams} and @water{50%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for amount) to the veg.

Stir together, then add the @mangetout{80%grams} and cook until the sauce has thickened slightly, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir the cooked noodles through the fragrant sauce and toss until well combined.

Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Share the sticky Thai style noodles between your bowls.

Sprinkle over the @salted peanuts{25%grams} and coriander.

Squeeze over some lime juice to finish.  
Enjoy!